ity, DCAM employs a BART-based DALM conditioned not only on pseudo-labeled data (as in DA2LM) but also on SDE-informed syntactic masks that preserve grammaticality. Training occurs in three phases: (1) pre-training SDE on unlabeled target text via dependency reconstruction; (2) joint training of DCAM and SGAM using synthetic divergence-augmented samples; and (3) end-to-end fine-tuning with a multi-objective loss combining disambiguation accuracy, structural consistency (via tree-edit distance), and cross-domain contrastive alignment. SAF-NED enables faster convergence, better generalization in structurally distant domains, and improved interpretability through explicit structural mediation. It addresses a critical gap in current NED systems: the lack of proactive, linguistically informed adaptation mechanisms. By shifting from uncertainty-driven reaction to structure-aware anticipation, SAF-NED offers a more principled and efficient path toward robust, low-resource cross-domain entity linking.",
  "Title": "Structural-Aware Adaptive Fusion for Cross-Domain Neural Entity Disambiguation",
  "Experiment": "The experimental design consists of four stages: (1) Data Preparation: We use AIDA-CoNLL as the source domain and evaluate on NEDMed, TweetNER, and LEGAL-NER. Unlabeled corpora from each target domain are collected to train the SDE and DCAM. Dependency trees are parsed using Stanza and used to compute structural divergence metrics. (2) Model Implementation: The SDE is a lightweight BiLSTM with attention over dependency path embeddings, trained to reconstruct masked dependency relations. The DCAM uses a BART-large model conditioned on both pseudo-labels and SDE-generated syntactic templates (e.g., relative clause frames for appositives). The SGAM replaces the UMN, computing fusion weights via dot-product attention between PEM’s mention representations and SDE-derived structural profiles. (3) Training Pipeline: First, SDE is pre-trained via self-supervised dependency masking. Then, DCAM is fine-tuned on augmented samples guided by high-divergence regions. Finally, the full SAF-NED system is trained end-to-end using a hybrid loss: L = α*L_ce + β*L_struct + γ*L_contrast, where L_struct penalizes syntactic inconsistency in generated contexts. Alternating optimization ensures stable convergence. (4) Evaluation: We measure zero-shot and few-shot F1, inference latency, calibration error, and human-rated context quality. Baselines include ADAPET, DA2LM, SSADP, and the original UMN-based dialogue model. Ablations test SDE impact, SGAM efficacy, and template utility. Ideal outcomes include >12% F1 gain over ADAPET in zero-shot setting, 30% faster convergence than iterative dialogue models, and superior syntactic coherence in human evaluation.",
